Londen m. George Cole
mij last to you was on the curt. sence non from you, yd cloverseed
are ships aboard Ewings, whr is now ready to saile m. Coots has send
mee not yett the charges, so s nept post the acctt. shell follow.

londen m. Abram Vivian
I have before mee yd. of 17h past, with invoyce of bayes bought, which I hope
ane ships aboard Pindar, tho is to sacke first. I have exspected sence to receave pe
of shecloathes desired as also to heare suither from you, though I exspect the hou
to see you here dayly, & then to in large by word of month, so pray in answer
hen of sett mee know what passes to goad, mj self accordingly whilss now I remanes
Londen m. Henry Marynard
mij last unto you was on the 4t ccortt the reds then mentioned must be assorted 2 of 48-
2 of £9, 2of £10, & 2 of £10:10, & 2 of £11- on auroiard to make a good affortiments
for I have not a bove 28 in all ressing yett I must have good, and penniewortht
or non, now have percaved bouth yd of 20 & 24t past, where by you will provide
the pack whites mentioned, & the 3 resting G.W. silver marck, which is soone as you
have you must engage him for 5 or lo more. I have given you creditt for the
goods aboard Pindar, which ray god send speedly over, also ben: clarck, butt itt makes
vere heard weather upon our coast, I can not butt wonder why you should ship so
many goods for mee in one bottom, whece you have the contrary order, & there by
all the cottens, & callicoss in one the same vessel, that is the right way to bring
mee either to declare the 90dds, or to loose them att the ensue att Bruges, for
besides that I beleave that slanck shall have opened some of the packes if not
all, seeng they came last on his board so itt will give suspition, where as to the contrane
iff in each vessel there is one or 2 packen they mught pass, I wonder m. Scawen would say
that I am in haste for them, where he knows I have yett such a quartitie by mee, & did
itl onely to have them come wish good time & leasure. Inclosed the acctt of sale of the
3 moits last, where by you will finde more of the old goods sold, then I exspected, so do
my ulmost endeavorr to putt them of well. I exspect to know what is solution you have
of the makeing of ssammets, as to the pattarne send you, as for frises, mee thinckes
itt where best to hold to severall drop cullours, because the browne do casely spot
if they be not mixt, wall sent of drap cullours will be best, butt non yallowish I boutt
I shall not sell that com as least yeare I could, in case J.S. of Brussels hath
the same, for he hath given them cuurant by att 3 a 4 Itivers anell cheaper then
I did: the walloones begon to demand them last yeare, which would partely incorridge
mee to have an other touch with him in July, butt recommend the makers to stop the
holes, which they leave so many in them, besides great faults of witts some ½ ayd
long: the bustijnes of JB. seem to bee not vere well revery day bills on him
potessed, fure he hath been over charged, for I do not know who would accept
so much att a time, yett I hope non shall loose ly him, I doubt you are much
engaged, I shall endeavoair to send you more remises &
